The Nigerian military has described as malicious a video alleging brutality by uniform men enforcing the lockdown order directive of the president. On the first day of the lockdown order,videos of uniform men neutralising citizens who defied the stay at home order surfaced online showing dehumanizing treatment meted on citizens by security agents. However in reaction, the coordinator of Directorate of Defence Media Operations Major General John Enenche in a statement said the videos were incidences of the past between 2012 and 2013. “Consequently, the Armed Forces of Nigeria wishes to state that the videos  were old clips of past incidents that took place in 2012 and 2013 respectively. “The clips are being used by some mischievous elements to tarnish the image of the Armed Forces of Nigeria. Those videos are misleading, as they are not related to the present military engagement of the Armed Forces of Nigeria towards the lockdown on COVID-19. The Nigerian Armed Forces sees those clips as calculated attempts to tarnish its professional integrity by some mischief makers,” he added  While urging the general public to disregard those videos, he said “It is the handwork of false news propagators,” The coordinator added that the Armed Forces of Nigeria remains undaunted and would not be distracted as it is committed to performing its constitutional roles towards ensuring the protection of the nation’s territorial integrity and the lives and property of the general public.     